Scope of the EIK Standard

The Shunyaya Execution Identity Kernel (EIK) defines a deterministic methodology for producing execution identity certificates representing the observable boundary of a program execution.

An execution identity certificate represents a canonical structural fingerprint of the execution boundary.

Conceptually:

E = Φ(P, I, O)

Where:

P = program
I = inputs
O = outputs

The certificate is produced by canonicalizing the execution boundary and generating a deterministic cryptographic hash.

Conceptually:

Φ(P,I,O) = SHA256(JSON_canonical(B))

Where:

B = (
  program_hash,
  argv,
  stdin,
  stdout,
  stderr,
  exit_code
)

This hash becomes the execution identity certificate.

Deterministic Identity Discipline

The EIK methodology follows three deterministic rules.

Replay Identity
same execution boundary → same certificate

Mutation Sensitivity
changed execution boundary → changed certificate

Restoration Identity
restored boundary → restored certificate

These rules define deterministic execution identity.

What EIK Does NOT Do

The EIK standard does not:

• modify classical computation
• alter algorithm outputs
• introduce probabilistic inference
• perform machine learning
• inject predictive models
• simulate future behavior
• introduce randomness
• alter execution semantics

It provides deterministic execution identity certification only.

Conformance

An implementation conforms to the EIK Standard if it:

• executes deterministically
• captures observable execution boundaries
• canonicalizes the execution boundary deterministically
• produces stable identity certificates for identical boundaries
• produces different certificates when boundaries differ

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• nondeterministic output ordering
• hidden state mutation
• tolerance-based comparison
• adaptive runtime mutation

does not conform to the deterministic EIK standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.

